DIPHTHERIA, IMPORTED - UK: BACKGROUND
*************************************
A ProMED-mail post
See Also
Diphtheria, imported - UK 970616231044
Diphtheria, imported - UK (02) 970915202723
Date: Tue, 16 Sep 1997 07:29:20 -0700
From: "Dr. Steve Berger" <mberger@post.tau.ac.il>
Source: Extracted from GIDEON software

England and Wales report infant vaccine coverage of 93%. As of 1995,
routine vaccination (DTP) is given age ages 2, 3 and 4 months; DT at age 4
years.
Fifty to 60% of laboratories in the United Kingdom routinely culture throat
swabs for _Corynebacterium diphtheriae_.
Thirty-seven cases [of diphtheria were reported in 1957; 1 in 1986; 2 in
1987; 4 in 1988; 6 in 1989; 4 in 1990; 1 in 1991; 3 in 1992; 5 in 1993; 9
in 1994; 13 in 1995; 12 in 1996; 15 first half of 1997 (England and Wales).
Thirty-three isolates of toxigenic _Corynebacterium diphtheriae_ were
reported during 1986 to 1993 - 18 of these imported from Indian
subcontinent. A single imported case (from the Baltic region) was
registered in 1997 (to this report).
Three hundred seventeen isolates of nontoxigenic _C. diphtheriae_ were
isolated during 1990 to 1995 (17 in 1990 and 135 in 1995) - 75% of these
were biotype var gravis.
Northern Ireland reports infant vaccine coverage of 95%.
Scotland reports infant vaccine coverage of 95%. Disease was reported
during 1975 [frequency?. No cases were reported during 1976 to 1993. Two
cases were reported in 1994; 4 in 1995; 5 in 1996 (1
associated with Eastern Europe); 1 during the first half of 1997.
Wales reported no cases during 1981 to 1994.
--
Steve Berger
mberger@post.tau.ac.il
